   {:e #blake3 "1b7e4719ae0bb47324781994d77e65e1f0fa0665f8cb7b472ee0707d8ce6d11b" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :task/t-4bb538d0; Session entity: :recon/trace-b8b893efbc3d3094; Session entity: :task/t-6897ffca; Session entity: :task/t-c6e5d966; CROSS-AGENT-PREMIUM: When Agent A's architecture observation connects to Agent C's spec divergence finding, the connection reveals an insight neither agent could see alone. Cross-agent connections carry a KNOWLEDGE SYNTHESIS PREMIUM — they are more valuable than intra-agent connections because they bridge independent perspectives. Implementation: in connect_observations(), detect cross-agent pairs via :exploration/source attribute. Apply 0.5x threshold for cross-agent connections (lower bar = more cross-agent links). Apply 1.5x weight multiplier for cross-agent connection weight in FEGH graph. This means cross-agent bridges rank higher in hypothesis output. The multi-agent daemon scenario (multiple agents writing to same store via daemon) is the primary use case for this. Verification: after 3 agents each record 5 observations, cross-agent connections outnumber intra-agent connections.; Session entity: :task/t-981b7412; Session entity: :task/t-b6d50fb7; Convergence Engine Architecture; Session entity: :recon/trace-39d16de1d28459cb; Session entity: :task/t-8fc96d15; PERCOLATION-THRESHOLD: There exists a critical observation density N_c where the auto-connected knowledge graph transitions from disconnected islands to a giant connected component. Below N_c, FEGH cannot generate meaningful bridges (too fragmented). Above N_c, bridge quality improves rapidly (communities are detectable). The structural bootstrap's job is to inject enough initial hypotheses to cross N_c. This is a PHASE TRANSITION, not a gradual improvement. For scale-free networks with power-law degree distribution, the percolation threshold is lower than for random graphs — hub structure helps. Monitoring: the number of connected components in the observation graph should be tracked. When it drops to a small number (say <=3), the graph has percolated and FEGH enters the semantic phase. Implementation: in connect_observations(), after creating connections, count connected components. If components > 5 and F(S) < 0.2, the graph is still fragmented — continue generating structural hypotheses. If components <= 3, transition to semantic phase.; Session entity: :task/t-b9f2fd31; PHASE-BOUNDARIES: Three-phase hypothesis generation governed by F(S) as continuous temperature. Phase 0 STRUCTURAL BOOTSTRAP: F(S)<0.2, signal=filesystem structure, hypothesis_count=ceil((1-F(S))*10)=9-10, community_granularity=coarse (min_community_size=ceil((1-F(S))*20)=16-20), broad open-ended questions. Phase 1 SEMANTIC EXPLORATION: 0.2<=F(S)<0.6, signal=observation keyword connections, hypothesis_count=4-8, communities formed from auto-connected hubs, targeted bridges between observation clusters. Phase 2 LOGICAL REFINEMENT: F(S)>=0.6, signal=spec-impl alignment gaps + contradiction detection, hypothesis_count=1-4, fine-grained communities, precise testable predictions. SMOOTH TRANSITIONS: At F(S)=0.3, generate both structural (weight=0.7*(1-F(S)/0.2)=0.35) and semantic (weight=0.65) hypotheses. The weights blend continuously. No hard switch. This is the annealing schedule made explicit.\nConnection Graph Percolation; Seed Domain Awareness; Observation-Aware Routing Dampening; Temperature-Adaptive Bridge Count; No Connection Noise; Bootstrap Hypothesis Completeness" :op :assert}
